On April 30, 2010, all of the outstanding common stock of 1st Financial Bank was acquired by Aslin Group, Inc. in exchange for a cash payment of $1. Concurrent with the acquisition, 1st Financial Bank was renamed Alterra Bank (the Bank). At that date, the Bank's liabilities exceeded its assets by $3,012,267. The acquisition was accounted for under the provisions of FASB ASC 805 (SFAS 141R. Business Combinations). Accordingly, the Bank adjusted the carrying values of the acquired tangible and identifiable intangible assets and the assumed liabilities to their estimated fair values.????2. In addition, the Bank recorded goodwill of $2,631,117. FASB ASC 805 allows a measurement period of up to one year to adjust initial fair value estimates as an additional information regarding such fair values as of the acquisition date becomes available.????3. Concurrent with the acquisition of the Bank, Aslin Group, Inc. contributed additional cash capital of $12,500,000 to the Bank, which represents the opening shareholders equity balance as of April 30, 2010.????4. As a result of the application of FASB ASC 805 and ASC 310-30, the April 30, 2010 balance sheet for Alterra Bank did not include an allowance for loan losses. The current provision and allowance for loan losses reflected as of September 30 is related to the growth in the loan portfolio since the acquisition.????5. Income reported in Schedules RI represents income since the acquisition date.

Error involves push down accounting requirements of ESOP debt reflected on parent holding company financial statements, but not previously reflected on bank statements. The relevant accounting principles as applied to this situation are technical, unclear and open to interpretation. Bank management became aware of the error in September 2010 and took immediate steps to avoid material deviations in bank equity capital from prior reporting periods via a corresponding contribution of equity from the parent holding company (See Schedule RI-A #11 and Schedule RI-E #5.a). Organizational structure and resources of parent holding company are such that these steps could and would have been taken earlier had bank management been earlier aware of the error. In addition, the portion of other-than- temporary losses recorded at 12/31/09 determined to be associated with credit losses have increased and the losses associated with other factors have decreased.  As such, the additional credit losses reduced earnings and were reversed from other comprehensive income.  To reflect this activity, Schedule RI line M.14.a. should be $143 and line M.14.b. should be $(7,057), resulting in a loss of $7,200 on line M.14.c.
